{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PLAN REVIEW · CONTAINER · [G4] Child consistency — pairing (parent 6f2d ⟶ child 4024 WS-DOC), cross-checked against the complete authoritative 2-child roster [WS-DOC (4024) + WS-EVAL-EXISTING (b4af)] — VERDICT: 1 finding (ordering/sequencing).\n\nScope note: per the authoritative SCOPE-DECISION on 6f2d (and the epic body's \"REMAINING (this epic's only live deliverables)\" line), the live residual scope is exactly WS-DOC + WS-EVAL-EXISTING (WS-VISUAL-EVAL split into its own epic yip-gem-teak/7013; WS-MIGRATE/WS-PROMPTS/WS-CLEANUP/WS-VISUAL/WS-VALIDATE/WS-INTENT-ALIGN all DONE via closed sibling epics 5766/72d5/e6d9/681b). So the 7-mode cross-child check runs WS-DOC against exactly one live sibling: WS-EVAL-EXISTING (b4af).\n\n7-mode audit (CLEAN except ordering):\n- Implicit shared state — CLEAN. Both children touch the eval seam, but the division is BUILD (b4af) vs DOCUMENT (4024); WS-DOC reads what WS-EVAL-EXISTING produces (\"reflects WS-EVAL-EXISTING as built\"). No undeclared shared mutable artifact; b4af does not silently depend on anything 4024 mutates.\n- Conflicting assumptions — CLEAN. The two-tier eval model is described identically on both sides: deterministic gate on every PR at zero API cost + LLM-judge tier OFF the PR critical path (workflow_dispatch + weekly schedule, non-blocking/continue-on-error, response-cached, concurrency-capped, fork-safe, spend-cap-guided). WS-DOC AC4 and WS-EVAL-EXISTING AC4/AC5 agree on tiers, triggers, and rails — no contradiction.\n- Scope overlap — CLEAN. Documenting the eval seam (4024) vs building it + finishing the run machinery (b4af) is a clean labor split, not duplication. b4af claims no documentation deliverable; 4024 claims no build deliverable.\n- Dependency gap — CLEAN (no missing producer). The doc's content dependency on the eval seam has a real producer in-roster (b4af); the dependency TARGET is not absent. The un-declared sequencing is captured as the ordering finding below.\n- Consumer impact — CLEAN / deferred. Per the epic's own agent-vs-single-turn bright line, G4 defers code-grounded consumer-impact to E4/G1G2/A1; no plan-level consumer breakage between the two siblings.\n- Residual references — CLEAN. WS-DOC names WS-EVAL-EXISTING accurately; no stale references to descoped/relocated workstreams (WS-VISUAL-EVAL / WS-MIGRATE et al.) as if they were live siblings of this epic.\n- Ordering violation — FINDING (below).\n\nFINDING (G4 · ordering violation):\n\n- finding: WS-DOC must document the eval seam \"as built\" by WS-EVAL-EXISTING, but no dependency/ordering link sequences the two — WS-DOC could be authored (and closed) before the seam it must mirror is finished, so the doc can be written against a moving/unbuilt target and silently drift.\n  - criteria: [G4]\n  - location: child 4024 WS-DOC — Scope bullet \"...how the live tier is triggered + cost/fork-safety rails (reflects WS-EVAL-EXISTING as built)\" and AC4 \"Documents the eval seam: two-tier model, how to author a spec, how the live tier is triggered, cost + fork-safety rails (consistent with WS-EVAL-EXISTING)\"; sibling b4af WS-EVAL-EXISTING AC3/AC4/AC5 (run_eval() live tier, eval-discipline + eval-live tiers being BUILT, fork-safety/spend-cap rails).\n  - evidence:\n    - WS-DOC explicitly binds its eval-seam documentation to WS-EVAL-EXISTING's delivered state: \"reflects WS-EVAL-EXISTING as built\" (Scope) and AC4 \"(consistent with WS-EVAL-EXISTING)\".\n    - The \"as built\" target does NOT yet exist: per the 6f2d SCOPE-DECISION comment and b4af's \"Why\", the live tier is presently an unwired stub — run_eval() raises NotImplementedError, deterministic scorer names are inert strings with no registry, and the eval-live step is a placeholder echo. b4af is the ticket that builds it (Phase 2.1–2.5: scorer registry, live solver + context-injection, datasets, fixtures, eval-live CI wiring + cost/fork-safety rails).\n    - ABSENCE confirmed against the whole roster: neither 4024 nor b4af carries a deps entry (both show \"deps\": []); there is no depends_on / blocked-by linking WS-DOC's authoring to WS-EVAL-EXISTING's completion. So nothing sequences \"document the seam\" after \"build the seam.\"\n  - scenarios:\n    - Both children are open, priority 2, no deps. WS-DOC is authored first; the cost/fork-safety rails and live-tier trigger mechanics are still in flux (or still stubbed) in b4af, so WS-DOC AC4 (\"how the live tier is triggered, cost + fork-safety rails\") documents an intended-but-unbuilt design that later drifts from b4af's actual eval-live CI wiring — re-introducing exactly the \"knowledge scattered / doc out of date\" problem WS-DOC exists to fix.\n    - Conversely, if b4af lands after WS-DOC closes, WS-DOC's \"consistent with WS-EVAL-EXISTING\" AC cannot be truthfully verified at WS-DOC close time (the comparand does not yet exist).\n  - impact: Low-to-moderate sequencing risk. Not a contradiction (the two descriptions agree today), but the cross-child binding is asserted (\"as built\", \"consistent with\") with no ordering link to enforce it, so the doc's eval-seam section can be completed against a moving/unbuilt target and silently drift, defeating the doc's own purpose.\n  - checklist_item: Check the 7 cross-child modes — ordering violation.\n  - suggested_fix: Add an explicit ordering link so the eval-seam SECTION of WS-DOC follows WS-EVAL-EXISTING's eval-live delivery — e.g. a depends_on (or blocked-by) from 4024 → b4af scoped to the eval-seam AC, OR split WS-DOC's eval-seam documentation to land in the same change as / immediately after b4af's eval-live CI wiring. If the team intends WS-DOC to be authored first as a design anchor, state that direction explicitly (WS-EVAL-EXISTING implements the seam WS-DOC specifies) and make b4af responsible for reconciling the doc to the as-built rails at its close, so the \"consistent with WS-EVAL-EXISTING\" AC has a defined enforcement point.\n\n(Note: an identical ordering finding was previously recorded on this pairing at timestamp 1782579130344411001; this re-affirms it after the full 7-mode re-check. The mirror b4af-side pairing correctly treats b4af as the producer carrying no independent ordering obligation, so the interaction is owned here and not double-counted there.)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782579768997254001,"uuid":"bb67aac9-4b1f-4ee1-ab80-b0b678590864"}